{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/squint-in-children/diagnosis/identification/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"2559b5e2-6604-5ca4-b15e-d51eb712aee4","slug":"identification","fullItemName":"Identification","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field dc8b2c36-8a22-4859-8c8b-ac820139483f --><h2>How can I identify a child with a squint?</h2><!-- end field dc8b2c36-8a22-4859-8c8b-ac820139483f -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item f2309c1f-2524-4b4b-adf2-3545746db600 --><!-- begin field 9035f41a-7449-4bc7-9d9f-ac820139483f --><ul><li><strong>Routine eye checks are offered to children to promptly identify reduced vision and other eye conditions.</strong><ul><li>Within 72 hours of birth, the child's eyes will be checked for any obvious physical problems as part of the newborn physical examination.</li><li>Between 6–8 weeks old, a follow-up physical examination is done to check for any obvious problems that were not picked up soon after birth.</li><li>At school entry (around 4 or 5 years of age), vision screening is offered to all children to identify common causes of reduced vision, including refractive error (long- or short-sightedness) and squint. </li></ul></li><li>Also, a parent or carer may present with a concern that their child's eye is 'turning'. <ul><li>Any complaint of a 'turning eye' should be taken seriously even if this cannot be reproduced in a consultation, as the squint may be intermittent.</li><li>Intermittent deviation of the eyes is common in healthy neonates and should not cause undue concern in an otherwise healthy baby. However, any constant squint, even in neonates, is significant. Normal binocular coordination is established at about 3 months, and any squint after this age is significant.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 9035f41a-7449-4bc7-9d9f-ac820139483f --><!-- end item f2309c1f-2524-4b4b-adf2-3545746db600 -->","topic":{"id":"d25cf803-28cb-5afd-80ca-d978